 for bestpractices and # AI Generation Engine (Study Builder)

## Overview
Develop the AI Generation Engine (Study Builder) for StudySpark: a core AI service that synthesizes uploaded materials, topic, child profile, and learning style into structured study sets. Output will include lessons, flashcards, quizzes, and printable layouts. The system supports iterative prompts for revisions, versioning, and safe, loop-aware feedback. It integrates with an LLM provider, preprocesses content, moderates safety, streams progressive generation previews, stores draft/version history, and enforces usage quotas with caching.

This prompt is designed to guide an AI development tool to implement end-to-end functionality across frontend, backend, and integration layers, with robust runtime safety (null/undefined guards, proper defaulting, and typed data handling) as mandated.

---

## Components to Build
1) AI Generation Engine Core (Study Builder Service)
- Purpose: Orchestrate content synthesis from inputs, manage prompt templates, context window management, and iterative revision logic.
- Subsystems:
  - Preprocessing Pipeline: upload material normalization, OCR/photo enhancement, chunking, summary extraction, topic tagging.
  - Prompt Template Engine: modular prompts for study sets, flashcards, quizzes, and printed layouts; supports dynamic context sizing and instruction tuning.
  - Safety & Moderation Layer: filter for inappropriate content; guardrails for age-appropriate material; audit logging.
  - Streaming Generator: publish partial results as they’re generated for progressive UI preview; handle backpressure and partial JSON streaming.
  - Versioning & Diffing: draft storage per input set, version graph, diffs, restore, and branching.
  - Rate Limiting & Quotas: per-user/plan limits, burst controls, cache repeated inputs.
  - Content Assembly: output structure (lessons, flashcards, quizzes, printable layouts) with meta-data (topic, age, learning style, version, timestamps).
  - Security & Auditing: logs, tamper-evidence, and access controls for study sets and revisions.

2) Frontend UI Components
- Study Builder Canvas: central workspace showing live AI-generated study sets with stream preview.
- Upload & Topic Panel: input for topic, file uploads (documents/images), teacher-provided notes.
- Child Profile & Learning Style Panel: age, grade, preferred learning style, accessibility options.
- Settings & Iteration Panel: prompts controls, revision requests, and versioning actions (save as draft, approve, refine, upgrade).
- Preview & Print Layouts: printable layouts (PDF-like) for lessons and flashcards; toggles for printable vs. interactive in-app experiences.
- Progress & Status Dashboard: real-time streaming status, ETA, reliability indicators, version history timeline.
- Navigation: top bar with user avatar, progress bar, bottom navigation for sections, collapsible filters for subjects/topics.
- Cards & Interaction: rounded, pastel-themed cards with hover/active states, pill-shaped tags, iconography, micro-interactions.
- Accessibility: keyboard navigability, screen-reader friendly labels, high-contrast mode toggles.

3) Backend APIs & Services
- Auth & User Management: authentication, authorization, role-based access; plan quotas.
- Upload Service: handling of materials (PDF, DOCX, images, text), storage links, and metadata extraction.
- Preprocessing Service: content summarization, chunking, topic tagging; returns context-ready blocks.
- Generation API: orchestrates LLM calls, manages context windows, and streaming results; handles retries, fallbacks.
- Moderation API: safety checks with logs; blocks disallowed content.
- Versioning API: create, diff, restore, tag versions; branching support.
- Publishing/Export API: render printable layouts (PDF/HTML), export data formats.
- Cache & Rate Limiting: in-memory and persistent cache for repeated inputs; per-user quotas.
- Datastore: schemas for users, studies, drafts, versions, materials, prompts, logs.

4) Integration & Infrastructure
- LLM Integration: support for OpenAI GPT-4o or equivalent; API keys management; prompt templates; system, vs messages; context window budgeting.
- Streaming Mechanisms: server-sent events or WebSocket streaming for progressive previews.
- Data Validation & Safety: input validators, schema guards, and runtime null safety checks.
- Observability: tracing, metrics, logging, error reporting, health checks.
- CI/CD & Packaging: modular microservices or monolith with clear boundaries; feature flags for iterative experiments.
- Data Security & Compliance: encryption at rest/in transit; age-appropriate data handling; access controls.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- UI Library: adopt design system with rounded UI, pastel palette, responsive grids.
- Components & Pages:
  - UploadPanel: drag-and-drop, multi-file support, previews.
  - TopicEditor: topic input with suggestions and auto-tagging.
  - ChildProfilePanel: age, learning style, accessibility options.
  - IterationPanel: controls to request refinements, adjust prompts, set versioning.
  - LivePreviewPanel: streaming generation results; partial lessons/flashcards/quizzes as they are produced.
  - LayoutPreview: printable layouts with print-friendly styles and toggle for in-app print view.
  - VersioningPanel: list of versions with diff views and restore action.
  - StatusBadge & Progress: real-time streaming indicator, ETA, and reliability.
  - SettingsDrawer: quotas, rate limits, preferences.
- State Management: useState<T[]>([]) defaults; ensure array protections with (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray checks; initialize all array states to [].
- Data Safety: Guard all API responses; validate shapes using TypeScript types; use optional chaining for nested data.
- Accessibility: aria-labels, keyboard shortcuts, proper color contrast.
- Performance: progressive rendering, debounced inputs, memoization for heavy render paths.

### Backend
- API Endpoints (example structure):
  - POST /api/v1/studies/prepare: accepts topic, uploadedMaterials, childProfile, learningStyle; returns draft context.
  - POST /api/v1/studies/generate: starts generation; supports streaming with SSE/WebSocket; accepts prompts overrides and versioning flags.
  - GET /api/v1/studies/{id}/stream: stream progress data and partial outputs.
  - POST /api/v1/studies/{id}/revise: submit revision prompt; returns updated draft.
  - POST /api/v1/studies/{id}/versions: create new version; returns version metadata.
  - GET /api/v1/studies/{id}/versions/{versionId}: fetch version data and diffs.
  - POST /api/v1/studies/{id}/approve: mark as final; exportable formats prepared.
  - POST /api/v1/moderate: run safety checks on content blocks.
- Database Tables / Schemas:
  - users: id, email, planTier, quotas, createdAt, updatedAt
  - studies: id, userId, topic, topicTags[], learningStyle, age, createdAt, updatedAt, status
  - materials: id, studyId, type (document/photo/text), sourceUrl, metadata
  - drafts: id, studyId, version, contentPayload (JSON), createdAt, updatedAt
  - versions: id, studyId, versionNumber, diffs, contentSnapshot (JSON), createdAt
  - prompts: id, studyId, role, content, createdAt
  - progress: studyId, stage, progressPct, streamingToken
  - moderations: id, studyId, status, issues, reviewedAt
  - quotas: userId, usedCount, windowStart, windowEnd
- Safety & Moderation:
  - Integrate safety filters (content moderation) before finalizing outputs.
- Streaming:
  - Implement SSE or WebSocket streams for progressive output chunks; ensure null-safe streaming of arrays and objects.
- Validation:
  - Use robust input validation; sanitize uploaded content; normalize data shapes; default missing fields to safe values.
- Performance & Caching:
  - Cache repeated generation inputs keyed by a deterministic hash of inputs; cache streaming chunks where appropriate.
- Security:
  - Implement token-based authentication; ensure authorization checks on study access; never expose raw materials publicly.

### Integration
- Data Flow:
  - Client uploads materials → Preprocessor → Context blocks → Generator with openAI prompts → Moderation → Assembly into study set structure → Versioned storage → Streaming preview to frontend.
- State Sync:
  - Ensure frontend reacts to streaming chunks; maintain a stable in-memory representation of current draft with safe null-handling.
- Error Handling:
  - Consistent error contracts; frontend-friendly error messages; retry policies for transient failures.

---

## User Experience Flow
1) User logs in and navigates to Study Builder (Study Spark).
2) User selects or creates a child profile (age, learning style) and sets topic.
3) User uploads teacher-provided materials (docs/images/photos) and optionally types notes or prompts.
4) Client triggers generation; streaming preview begins:
   - UI shows progressive generation of study components: lessons, flashcards, quizzes, printable layouts.
   - Users can pause, request refinements, or alter prompts (adjust difficulty, style, or format).
5) Safety moderation runs in parallel; any flagged content is highlighted; user can approve or request edits.
6) Generated draft exists as a draft version; user can save, view diffs against prior version, or restore.
7) User reviews in-app; can approve as final, or refine further. If approved, option to export printable layouts or share with child.
8) User can organize saved studies into folders, duplicate studies for reuse, or upgrade content as child progresses.
9) System enforces rate limits and quotas; provide clear feedback if limits are reached.
10) All actions are versioned; user can browse version history and revert to earlier states.

